⏺ The structure and CRS grouping are good — the two-subgraph split (surveyed vs. cloud) is a smart
  way to communicate the coordinate system boundary. A few issues and suggestions:

  Logical errors:

  1. cust_csv → emlid arrow is wrong. The customer control file ({customer}_{job}.csv from
  extract_dc_points.py) produces monument coordinates used for Emlid RS3 localization in the field —
  it doesn't produce {job}.csv. The Emlid survey CSV is an independent output of the field work. That
   arrow implies a data transformation that doesn't exist. Both feed into the process but
  independently.
  2. rmse_calc.py is missing its third input. It needs reconstruction.json + {job}_check.txt + the
  Emlid survey CSV ({job}_filtered.csv or {job}.csv). Only the first two are shown feeding into it.
  3. customer node is inside the "Surveyed" subgraph but only connects outside it (packager →
  customer, report → customer). Mermaid will place it inside the "Surveyed" box which looks odd — it
  should sit outside both subgraphs as a terminal node.

  Minor suggestions:

  4. filter has no display label — it'll render as just the word "filter" in a plain box. Adding
  filter(["filter (manual)"]) would clarify it.
  5. marks.csv for Pix4D is a dead-end by design, but a reader might wonder if it's an error. Could
  use a note style or just label it more clearly as a parallel output.
  6. Subgraph name "Web eg EPSG:32613" is a little opaque — "Cloud / EC2" or "Processing" might be
  clearer than "Web".

  Want me to make these corrections?

