on this topic                                                                                        

⏺ You're right that {job}_check.txt contains the surveyed coordinates (X, Y, Z from the Emlid CSV,
  copied in by prepare_odm.py). However, rmse_calc.py currently ignores those coordinates — it only
  reads the pixel observations (px, py, image, label) from the check file and uses the Emlid CSV
  directly for the ground truth XY Z. This was a design choice but it's redundant — the coordinates
  are already in the check file.

  The argument for removing the Emlid CSV input:
  - The check file already has the ground truth coordinates (they came from the Emlid CSV via
  prepare_odm.py)
  - Single input is simpler and less error-prone (no risk of passing mismatched CSV)
  - The check file is the authoritative artifact for this run

  The one thing to verify: rmse_calc.py currently uses g["lat"]/g["lon"] from parse_survey_csv to
  reproject ground truth to EPSG:32613 (after the bug fix we just did). The check file has X/Y
  already in EPSG:32613 — so we could read those directly instead, which is simpler and avoids the
  whole lat/lon reprojection path.

  Creating the bead:

